read in data

plant <- read_csv(here("data", "knb-lter-hfr.109.18","hf109-01-sarracenia.csv")) %>% 
  # make column names cleaner
  clean_names() %>% 
  # select columns of interest 
  select(totmass, species, feedlevel, sla, chlorophyll, amass, num_lvs, num_phylls)

subset dropping NA

plant_subset <- plant %>% 
  drop_na(sla, chlorophyll, amass, num_phylls, num_lvs)

create a correlation plot

“to determine the relationships between numerical variables in our dataset, we calculated pearsons r and visually represented correlation using a correlation plot”

# calculate Pearson's r for numerical values only
plant_cor <- plant_subset %>% 
  select(feedlevel:num_phylls) %>% 
  cor(method = "pearson")
#returns matrix of numerical values

#create a correlation plot 
corrplot(plant_cor,
         #change shape of cells 
         method = "ellipse",
         addCoef.col = "black")

#don't include two predictors (eg mass) because can conflate r^2

starting regression here: “to determine how species and physiological characters predict bimass, we fit multiple linear models”

# null = no predictors
null <- lm(totmass ~ 1, data = plant_subset)
# full = response and all potential predictors 
full <- lm(totmass ~ species + feedlevel + sla + chlorophyll + amass + num_lvs + num_phylls, data = plant_subset)

we visually asses normality and homoskedasticity of residuals using diagnostic plots for full model

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(full)

We also tested for normality using Shapiro-Wilk test (null: variable of interest (ie residuals) are normally distributed). We tested for heteroskedasticity using Breusch-Pagan test (null: variable of interest has constant variance)

check_normality(full)
## Warning: Non-normality of residuals detected (p < .001).
check_heteroscedasticity(full)
## Warning: Heteroscedasticity (non-constant error variance) detected (p < .001).

Non-normality & Heteroscedasticity; Assumptions of linear regression are not met!

mathematical transformation can make data betta (only transform response, predictors can stay on the same scale)

# log transform response
null_log <- lm(log(totmass) ~ 1, data = plant_subset)
full_log <- lm(log(totmass) ~ species + feedlevel + sla + chlorophyll + amass + num_lvs + num_phylls, data = plant_subset)

plot(full_log)

check normality of full model with log transform

# do any combo of predictors inflate the data (because they're related)
check_normality(full_log)
## OK: residuals appear as normally distributed (p = 0.107).
check_heteroscedasticity(full_log)
## OK: Error variance appears to be homoscedastic (p = 0.071).

they’re good now! meeting assumption on linear regression all interpretation will be based on a transformed response

Evaluate multicolinearity

car::vif(full_log)

We evaluated multcol by calculating generalized variance inflation factor and determined that there are no related predictors which inflate the data.

try some models addressing question: what set of predictor variables best explains the response

# species predicts biomass?

model2_log <- lm(log(totmass) ~ species, data = plant_subset)
# check assumptions for model 

plot(model2_log)

# clumps = predictor categorical, all good

check_normality(model2_log)
## OK: residuals appear as normally distributed (p = 0.374).
check_heteroscedasticity(model2_log)
## OK: Error variance appears to be homoscedastic (p = 0.100).
# conforms to assumptions of linear regression!

compare models using Akaike Info Criterion (AIC) values: (looks for the simplest model that explains the most variance)

AICc(full_log)
## [1] 133.9424
AICc(model2_log)    
## [1] 157.5751
AICc(null_log)
## [1] 306.0028
# least complex model that best predicts the response is full model (lowest value)
MuMIn::AICc(full_log, model2_log, null_log)

back transform estimates by exponentiating (because we took log)

model_pred <- ggpredict(full_log, terms = "species", back.transform = TRUE)
## Model has log-transformed response. Back-transforming predictions to
##   original response scale. Standard errors are still on the log-scale.
# reporting results in original variable is fine if you tell ppl that 

# "log transformed to meet assumptions, back transformed for ease of communication of results"
model_pred

different types of ANOVA

type 1: order matter; species > feed level > etc type 2: order doesnt mateer but there may be interaction type 3: order and interaction matters
